<font color="#FF0000">ANOTHER SIDE OF THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 21  6:11:51 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
My father was rarely outwardly emotional. I don't remeber<br>
him ever crying, until 1969. I was out of the draft,<br>
(physical defermeent) and was in college. Doing all<br>
that he had hoped I would do. Then I told him I was<br>
dropping out of college and spending full time working<br>
to stop the war. He knew it meant demonstrations, possible<br>
confrontations with police, arrest and maybe worst.<br><br>
He went to war in WWII, so that I would not have to face a<br>
situation like Vietnam.<br><br>
He felt it was sacraficing my life, and my personal<br>
ambitions, which scared him greatly. He grew up in the<br>
depression and having good job skills was the most <br>
important thing I could do to prepare for my adult<br>
life. He lived through the holocoust and knew the<br>
danger of confrontation with police and the state.<br><br>
The night I told him of my decision, he cried. I cried,<br>
knowing that my decisions hurt him and scared him and there<br>
was nothing I could do to make it any better. He called<br>
me a fool and worse.<br><br>
It wasn't until about 10 years after the war that my<br>
mother told me he was proud of me for what I did. When<br>
others did not like the war, they hid from it. I stood<br>
up and took a firm position. It wasn't until after the<br>
war that my parents could see that the anti-war movement<br>
was right to protest the war.
